title: Update AMD transpose to match CUDA transpose.
body:
**Description**:
Update ROCM's transpose.h|cc to match CUDA's transpose.h|cc (with rocm-specific code changes).
Delete ROCM transpose_impl.h|cc and use the hipified versions from CUDA.

**Motivation and Context**
Motivation is to minimize the difference between ROCM and CUDA code as much as possible.

Prior to ROCM 3.10, we required a workaround in Transpose where we manually allocated scratch buffers and `hipMemcpyAsync` them to the device, rather than passing as kernel parameters (to avoid a significant performance penalty).  As of ROCM 3.10, this workaround is no longer needed and we get the expected performance.

title: Remove temp buffer in ReduceScatter and AllGather; Add UTs for NCCL Kernels
body:
Removed the temp buffer used in the ReduceScatter and AllGather nodes, and rely on the contiguous inputs to enforce the wholeness of buffer. 
- To work with the buffer size requirement for ReduceScatter and AllGather, I have to introduce padding tensor to the end of inputs: Constant op is used to generated initializer padding for AllGather, ConstantOfShape op is used for generating activation padding for ReduceScatter. 

Introduced the long overdue unit tests for nccl kernels. 
- I have to introduce an Duplicated op, which is functionally same as Identity ops, but doesn't reuse the input buffer. This op is added to the single node testing graph to work around the constrain of graph inputs/outputs memory constrain. 
- Introduce an SetDevice API for OpTester to select GPU in distributed UT runs.

title: Windows training in C Sharp
body:
Added build and DLL support to orttraining to create onnxruntime.dll with training support for Windows x64 and extended Microsoft.ML with new OnnxTraining that allows training from within C# application.

Training in C is definitely faster, but training with C# has the advantage of easy data collection and preprocessing before feeding the data into the AI model.  This pull request adds the support needed to train ONNX models from a C# application where the data is loaded and preprocessed on the C# side, and then trained on the ONNX C++ side.  The error function is then also implemented on the C# side thus giving greater flexibility to create complex cost functions in C#.

Changes to existing Microsoft.ML and orttraining were kept to an absolute minimum.  If accepted, I would be happy to create a set of unit tests for this as well.

title: Remove ROCm element-wise workaround
body:
**Description**:
There was a compiler issue in versions before ROCm 4.0 when passing/accessing struct-based kernel parameters, which caused performance issues.  Now that ROCm 4.0 is released, we can remove the workaround.

This change makes the ROCm element-wise code as similar as possible to CUDA element-wise code.  After a few more changes (future pull request), the ROCm-specific code can be removed altogether.

**Performance impact:**
On BERT-Large, this improves throughput by ~4% on AMD GPUs.

Before this change, we can see the extra copies (and performance impact) for the element-wise kernels:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8907830/102836440-41aa9180-43ae-11eb-87b1-b77e3a945dcf.png)

After this change, the extra copies are gone:

title: Fix ImportError in build.py
body:
There is a possible ImportError where build.py can import the wrong 'util' package if there are others present in `sys.path` already

**Description**: 
You can get past this issue by replacing
`sys.path.append(os.path.join(REPO_DIR, "tools", "python"))`
with
`sys.path.insert(0, os.path.join(REPO_DIR, "tools", "python"))`

This ensures that onnxruntime's util library will always be first in sys.path

**Motivation and Context**
Fix to issue here: #6230 

The `tools/ci_build/build.py` script can import the wrong `util` library because `sys.path.**append**` can put the `util` library path after python site-packages path.

On my system, I already have python's site-packages on my path, so after
`sys.path.append(os.path.join(REPO_DIR, "tools", "python"))`
my `sys.path` is
`['/usr/local/lib/python3.7/site-packages', '/home/mgoin/code/onnx-runtime/tools/python']`

**Description**: Investigating a perf issue where-in a half-precision opset-11 model is substantially faster than a half-precision opset-12 model. Used the `onnxruntime_perf_test` executable and verified that the performance of both the opset-11 and opset-12 models are now on par with this change.  

**Motivation and Context**
Resolves https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6173 (used the model attached in the issue for debugging)
